<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,1276,1663]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Remarks.—The largest species of the genus with a body length about 
<quantity box="[940,1062,1276,1303]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="41.0" valueMax="42.0" valueMin="40.0">40–42 mm</quantity>
and wingspan about 
<quantity box="[1301,1437,1276,1303]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.03" metricValueMax="1.08" metricValueMin="0.98" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="103.0" valueMax="108.0" valueMin="98.0">98–108 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Distant, W. L." box="[159,307,1312,1338]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="335 - 338" refId="ref67810" refString="Distant, W. L. (1882) Descriptions of a new species and a new genus of Cicadidae from Madagascar. Transaction of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 1882, 335 - 338, plate XV. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1882. tb 01579. x" type="journal article" year="1882">Distant 1882</bibRefCitation>
). The body size, inflated male abdomen with a piceous posterior margin to the abdominal tergites, and bronzing restricted to the distal fore wing quickly distinguish the species from its congeneric species. The song is a series of short buzzes about 
<geoCoordinate box="[487,540,1384,1411]" degrees="1.5" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" precision="5555" value="-1.5">1.5 s</geoCoordinate>
in duration increasing in intensity to about 1 s with a short decrease in intensity followed by the loudest and most rapid production of timbal clicks completing the syllable with peak energy about 1.4 kHz (
<bibRefCitation author="Boulard, M." box="[254,428,1456,1483]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="1 - 181" refId="ref67329" refString="Boulard, M. (2006 b) Facultes acoustiques, ethologie sonore des cigales, entomophonateurs par excellence. Ecole Pratique des Hautes Etudes, Travaux du Laboratoire Biologie et Evolution des Insectes Hemipteroidea, 16, 1 - 181." type="journal article" year="2006">Boulard 2006b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,1276,1663]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Distribution.—The species is known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[754,889,1492,1518]" name="Madagascar" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Metcalf, Z. P." box="[907,1079,1492,1518]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="1 - 492" refId="ref69874" refString="Metcalf, Z. P. (1963 b) General catalogue of the Homoptera, Fascicle VIII. Cicadoidea. Part 2. Tibicinidae. North Carolina State College Contribution, 1564, i-vi + 1 - 492." type="journal article" year="1963">Metcalf 1963b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sanborn, A. F." box="[1094,1258,1492,1518]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" refId="ref70566" refString="Sanborn, A. F. (2013) Catalogue of the Cicadoidea (Hemiptera: Cicadoidea). With contributions to the bibliography by Martin H. Villet. Elsevier / Academic Press, San Diego, 1001 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / b 978 - 0 - 12 - 416647 - 9.00001 - 2" type="book" year="2013">Sanborn 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Jacobi, A." box="[1280,1436,1492,1518]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="519 - 552" refId="ref68988" refString="Jacobi, A. (1917) Die Zikadenfauna Madagascars und der Comoren. Reise in Ostafrika in den Jahren 1903 - 1905 mit Mitteln der Hermann und Elise geb. Heckmann Wentzel-Stiftung ausgef ʾ hrt von Professor Dr. Alfred Voeltzkow. Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse. Systematische Arbeiten, 3, 519 - 552. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 64840" type="journal article" year="1917">Jacobi (1917)</bibRefCitation>
reported the species from 
<collectingRegion box="[440,595,1528,1554]" country="Madagascar" name="Antananarivo" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Antananarivo</collectingRegion>
, central 
<collectingCountry box="[690,827,1528,1554]" name="Madagascar" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
